00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:19.600
Last year, I was at I/O here
to present material design.

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:22.210
And one of the things
that attracted me

00:01:22.210 --> 00:01:26.610
to Cardboard and to VR, if
you think about material

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:31.030
design, its origins
are in the fact

00:01:31.030 --> 00:01:35.270
that you're physically
interacting with software.

00:01:35.270 --> 00:01:37.860
So the way in which
you respond to it,

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:39.780
you're touching
a physical device

00:01:39.780 --> 00:01:41.530
and you're actually
touching the software,

00:01:41.530 --> 00:01:44.020
and in that, you kind want
to have the software have

00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:45.961
some authenticity, right?

00:01:45.961 --> 00:01:47.460
It's going to be
responsive and it's

00:01:47.460 --> 00:01:53.170
going to have some physics,
and motion is a first priority

00:01:53.170 --> 00:01:54.650
citizen there.

00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:56.610
You want to be true
to that interaction.

00:01:56.610 --> 00:02:00.580
And the cool thing about that
is that every single time

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:04.590
that computing gets closer to
the way in which we naturally

00:02:04.590 --> 00:02:07.120
interact with the world,
that's where the magic happens.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:10.199
Well, virtual
reality is 10x that.

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:12.630
It's really tapping
directly into the way

00:02:12.630 --> 00:02:14.740
we perceive and see the world.

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:16.300
If you can get one
of these demos,

00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:19.900
and again, those jump videos,
you have to see them in VR.

00:02:19.900 --> 00:02:22.202
That's really
where the magic is.

00:02:22.202 --> 00:02:23.910
Near things are near,
far things are far,

00:02:23.910 --> 00:02:27.910
and it's really tapping
into that authenticity

00:02:27.910 --> 00:02:29.820
of the physical space.

00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:32.670
And we really feel like
in terms of creating

00:02:32.670 --> 00:02:35.200
delightful experiences, that's
really where the magic is.

00:02:35.200 --> 00:02:37.070
When computing gets
closer to the way

00:02:37.070 --> 00:02:39.110
that humans naturally
interact with the world,

00:02:39.110 --> 00:02:43.720
that's where great
things can happen.

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:45.732
But the inverse is also true.

00:02:45.732 --> 00:02:48.960
We raised the stakes in terms
of people's expectations.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:53.850
We expect reality to not drop
frames, and virtual reality,

00:02:53.850 --> 00:02:55.350
if we really want
it to be immersive

00:02:55.350 --> 00:02:57.060
and have a great
experience, we want

00:02:57.060 --> 00:02:58.935
to make sure that we're
doing the right thing

00:02:58.935 --> 00:03:01.000
and we're feeding into
people's expectations

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.350
about turning around and seeing
things and how that works.

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:06.980
And so it's easy
to fall into a pit

00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:09.244
where actually, you can
create a bad experience,

00:03:09.244 --> 00:03:10.910
just as much as it
is possible to create

00:03:10.910 --> 00:03:12.564
an amazing experience.

00:03:12.564 --> 00:03:14.230
And we've been thinking
about that a lot

00:03:14.230 --> 00:03:16.766
since we started
working on Cardboard,

00:03:16.766 --> 00:03:19.586
and we're actually really
excited about the momentum

00:03:19.586 --> 00:03:21.710
across the entire industry
and lots of conversation

00:03:21.710 --> 00:03:24.090
about how to design
great experiences.

00:03:24.090 --> 00:03:26.482
And today, we're going to
share what excites us about VR,

00:03:26.482 --> 00:03:28.337
and we're also
going to share what

00:03:28.337 --> 00:03:30.920
we've learned in the short time
that we've been working on it,

00:03:30.920 --> 00:03:33.420
and we hope to continue
this conversation

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:35.100
beyond these walls.

00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:37.434
So with that, please
welcome Erica.

00:03:37.434 --> 00:03:40.278
