one exclamation point--

00:05:07.030 --> 00:05:09.260
players get to dive
off of buildings,

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:12.450
and that feeling of falling
continuously is an experience

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:15.750
you can't easily
get in real life.

00:05:15.750 --> 00:05:20.650
So those are a few of the many
compelling use cases for VR.

00:05:20.650 --> 00:05:22.620
What are you going to make?

00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:24.400
I imagine that some
of you have ideas

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:26.589
for apps that will
live entirely in VR,

00:05:26.589 --> 00:05:28.380
but I'm guessing that
a large number of you

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:30.290
have existing 2D
apps that you're

00:05:30.290 --> 00:05:32.016
thinking about adapting to VR.

00:05:32.016 --> 00:05:34.380
And to those folks,
my tip to you

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:37.110
is to start small and
focus on introducing

00:05:37.110 --> 00:05:42.224
VR content that for your
app is a game changer.

00:05:42.224 --> 00:05:44.390
To give you a better idea
of what I'm talking about,

00:05:44.390 --> 00:05:49.210
let's imagine I have a
hypothetical real estate app.

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:52.900
We have a Map view that allows
you to filter by location.

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:54.770
We have individual
listings with information

00:05:54.770 --> 00:05:56.470
about price and size.

00:05:56.470 --> 00:05:57.950
We even integrate
with Google Maps,

00:05:57.950 --> 00:06:00.780
allowing you to easily get
locations to each house.

00:06:00.780 --> 00:06:05.295
All of these tools are
working really well in 2D.

00:06:05.295 --> 00:06:07.420
But one part of the app
that would work much better

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:10.250
in virtual reality
is the photo gallery

00:06:10.250 --> 00:06:13.510
because compared to
a series of photos,

00:06:13.510 --> 00:06:16.150
touring in the home in VR will
give you a much better sense

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:17.752
of scale and layout.

00:06:17.752 --> 00:06:19.210
Also, think how
much time you could

00:06:19.210 --> 00:06:22.245
save if you didn't have to
physically visit every house

00:06:22.245 --> 00:06:25.032
that you're interested in.

00:06:25.032 --> 00:06:26.865
Ask yourself if there's
any part of your app

00:06:26.865 --> 00:06:29.230
that is practically
begging to be displayed

00:06:29.230 --> 00:06:32.570
in virtual reality, and if you
do decide to incorporate VR

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:37.830
into your app, here are some
best practice guidelines.

00:06:37.830 --> 00:06:40.220
If you're using an icon to
represent Cardboard mode,

00:06:40.220 --> 00:06:42.810
we suggest using the
silhouetted white icon

00:06:42.810 --> 00:06:45.740
on the left instead of the
colored icon on the right.

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:47.720
The silhouetted icon
is simpler and it's

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:50.930
in keeping with the
Material Style Guide.

00:06:50.930 --> 00:06:54.060
If instead you're using a
text button entry point,

00:06:54.060 --> 00:06:56.152
say, something like View
in Cardboard or View

00:06:56.152 --> 00:06:58.240
in Virtual Reality,
using the word

00:06:58.240 --> 00:06:59.890
"cardboard" will
remind people what

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:02.290
they should be reaching for.

00:07:02.290 --> 00:07:05.710
And finally, many of your users
won't have Cardboard, at least

00:07:05.710 --> 00:07:07.910
yet, and for these
users, you might

00:07:07.910 --> 00:07:10.480
consider hiding
the future entirely

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.380
or, if you want to
promote it, direct them

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:14.290
to the Google
Cardboard site where

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:17.370
they can learn what Cardboard
is and potentially get

00:07:17.370 --> 00:07:18.500
a Cardboard of their own.

00:07:21.130 --> 00:07:24.950
This concept of introducing
VR into 2D apps is still new,

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:28.460
but there are already a number
of apps that are doing it.

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:29.950
On the left,
there's Monzo, which

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:32.810
is an app that allows you to
create digital models of cars,

00:07:32.810 --> 00:07:36.060
planes, even catapults,
and they added the ability

00:07:36.060 --> 00:07:39.240
to view your final creations
in virtual reality.

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:40.720
And on the right
is Seene, which is

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:43.810
an app that allows you to
create and view 3D photos,

00:07:43.810 --> 00:07:46.280
and they also added
a Cardboard mode.

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:47.860
And most recently,
at the keynote

00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:50.980
yesterday, we announced
that YouTube will support

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:52.725
Cardboard mode for 360 videos.

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:59.080
In a year's time, over a million
people have gotten Cardboard,

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:01.910
and that number is getting
larger and larger, which

00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:05.190
means you have a growing
audience for the apps

00:08:05.190 --> 00:08:06.190
that you will dream up.

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:11.190
And as you start building
these VR experiences,

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:13.857
it's important for you to
constantly test them out.

00:08:13.857 --> 00:08:15.940
I'd like to welcome Manuel,
who will tell you more

00:08:15.940 --> 00:08:18.656
about building VR experiences.

00:08:18.656 --> 00:08:21.644
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:25.090 --> 00:08:26.340
MANUEL CLEMENT: Thanks, Erica.

00:08:26.340 --> 00:08:26.940
OK.

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:29.170
Let's talk about crafting
your own applications.

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:30.390
How many of you make stuff?

00:08:32.521 --> 00:08:34.729
I just want to make sure
I'm at the right conference.

00:08:38.409 --> 00:08:43.230
So when you build
applications in VR,

00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:46.740
it's very important that
you try them as early and as

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:48.554
often as possible.

00:08:48.554 --> 00:08:50.470
It's kind of a temptation
to just throw things

00:08:50.470 --> 00:08:53.610
together and say it looks really
nice looking at your computer

00:08:53.610 --> 00:08:54.630
monitor.

00:08:54.630 --> 00:08:56.979
So something we think about
is the design process here,

00:08:56.979 --> 00:08:58.270
and we're just getting started.

00:08:58.270 --> 00:09:01.240
We want to share some ideas with
you, some things we explored.

00:09:01.240 --> 00:09:04.420
Just remember to put it in
Cardboard, put it on eyes.

00:09:04.420 --> 00:09:07.450
As you place objects, say, wow,
this is too close, too far.

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:08.870
We'll talk about it in a minute.

00:09:08.870 --> 00:09:13.030
So the goal here is to have
genuine empathy for your users.

00:09:13.030 --> 00:09:14.050
How do they feel?

00:09:14.050 --> 00:09:16.550
How does it really feel?

00:09:16.550 --> 00:09:20.457
So although this is about
prototyping and building stuff,

00:09:20.457 --> 00:09:21.790
we're building stuff for humans.

00:09:21.790 --> 00:09:24.520
Let's talk about humans.

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:27.170
First, I'd like to
talk about convergence.

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:29.970
Convergence is the
inward movement

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:32.620
your eyes make toward
each other when

00:09:32.620 --> 00:09:36.590
you're trying to keep sharpness
in objects you're looking at.

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:38.810
You might say it's focus.

00:09:38.810 --> 00:09:40.247
So a little experiment.

00:09:40.247 --> 00:09:41.580
Put your finger in front of you.

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:43.370
Look at it.

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:44.960
It's sharp.

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:49.837
And then you look at me or
at the stage, unsharp finger.

00:09:49.837 --> 00:09:50.670
You see two fingers.

00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:55.122
Next one.

00:09:55.122 --> 00:09:55.955
Is this comfortable?

00:09:55.955 --> 00:09:57.790
What do you think?

00:09:57.790 --> 00:10:00.430
So I did not experience this.

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:02.940
I didn't get traumatized, but
let's try to traumatize you.

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:06.650
Put your in front of you
and imagine it's a boulder,

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:08.620
and then bring it
toward your face.

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:10.080
Keep going, keep
going, keep going.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:13.360
At one point, for
a regular human,

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:16.240
it will be blurry
no matter what.

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:18.540
Basically, things that are
too close to your head,

00:10:18.540 --> 00:10:21.480
you can't focus on it,
you can't converge on it.

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:26.900
It's something really
important to think about,

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:30.627
and that's because your
eyes are basically crossing

00:10:30.627 --> 00:10:32.210
and you're straining
your eye muscles,

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:34.110
so there's comfort
there as well,

00:10:34.110 --> 00:10:35.610
discomfort for your
users, something

00:10:35.610 --> 00:10:38.240
to really think
about display stuff.

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:40.260
A few more things
about convergence/focus

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:45.130
is people can only
focus on one thing

00:10:45.130 --> 00:10:48.760
at a time, a finger or myself.

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:50.959
Also, switching
between distances.

00:10:50.959 --> 00:10:52.500
I'm looking at this
thing right here,

00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:54.412
and I'm looking at
people in the back,

00:10:54.412 --> 00:10:55.870
and I'm looking
here, and the back,

00:10:55.870 --> 00:10:58.012
and actually, the
thing is right here.

00:10:58.012 --> 00:10:59.720
If you do this
repeatedly, eventually, it

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:02.110
becomes uncomfortable, and
different people feel it

00:11:02.110 --> 00:11:04.840
differently, keep in mind.

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:08.650
Additionally, people are
better at judging distances

00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:11.130
between objects that are up
close-- kind of makes sense,

00:11:11.130 --> 00:11:11.630
right?

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:13.046
My hand's here or
my hand's here--

00:11:13.046 --> 00:11:18.560
than far away-- last
row, second to last.

00:11:18.560 --> 00:11:22.180
So the point here as you
build your applications

00:11:22.180 --> 00:11:24.840
is to always be aware of
what people's eyes have

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:25.690
to converge on.

00:11:25.690 --> 00:11:28.760
That's a good way
to think about it.

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:30.580
How does it relate
to you as developers?

00:11:30.580 --> 00:11:32.590
Well, it'll take you less time.

00:11:32.590 --> 00:11:33.950
You'll make less mistakes.

00:11:33.950 --> 00:11:37.030
You'll always try it and
say, are the eyes converging?

00:11:37.030 --> 00:11:38.450
Are people comfortable or not?

00:11:38.450 --> 00:11:41.660
So very useful for developers.

00:11:41.660 --> 00:11:43.704
So let's share some
prototypes with you.

00:11:43.704 --> 00:11:45.370
This is something we
tried a little bit,

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:48.050
and I'm just sharing with
you the design process here.

00:11:48.050 --> 00:11:51.500
In this tool we prototyped,
we have these outside rings,

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:57.300
and it presents you with a zone
of comfortable neutral/zero

00:11:57.300 --> 00:11:59.760
convergence for maximum comfort.

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:02.310
So you place objects
there and chances are,

00:12:02.310 --> 00:12:04.889
when people are focusing
back and forth in that area,

00:12:04.889 --> 00:12:05.930
they'll stay comfortable.

00:12:05.930 --> 00:12:07.720
So this was fun for us to try.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:10.302
Additionally, when objects
are too close to you,

00:12:10.302 --> 00:12:11.760
it's going to zoom
in at one point,

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:14.740
there's a smaller
red ring, and so

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:16.622
this was us checking things out.

00:12:16.622 --> 00:12:18.080
It's a good idea
to show the design

00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:21.650
tool at what point things
are too close to the person.

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:23.020
This is just sharing some ideas.

00:12:23.020 --> 00:12:24.920
We've learned a lot from this
prototype and other things

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:25.586
we're exploring.

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:29.380
Let's talk about scale.

00:12:29.380 --> 00:12:31.200
So in VR, scale
is very important,

00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:35.590
something key to think about
as you build your experience.

00:12:35.590 --> 00:12:39.560
So there's something called
IPD, Inter-Pupillary Distance,

00:12:39.560 --> 00:12:42.610
and it's the distance
between your pupils.

00:12:42.610 --> 00:12:46.860
So something interesting
is an accurate IPD

00:12:46.860 --> 00:12:51.160
ensures people's sense of
scale matches their perception

00:12:51.160 --> 00:12:53.900
of reality in the real world.

00:12:53.900 --> 00:12:57.490
That's like regular reality.

00:12:57.490 --> 00:12:58.950
But I could be giant.

00:12:58.950 --> 00:13:00.800
My head could be massive.

00:13:00.800 --> 00:13:02.556
My IPD could be very wide.

00:13:02.556 --> 00:13:04.305
Also, it would mean
you guys of the world,

00:13:04.305 --> 00:13:07.970
if I had a really large head,
would appear really tiny,

00:13:07.970 --> 00:13:09.380
and that's really fun.

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:10.740
So scale is fun.

00:13:10.740 --> 00:13:13.280
Have fun with it.

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:15.040
To understand scale
better, something else

00:13:15.040 --> 00:13:17.670
we prototyped a bit is, what
if we dropped a human body

00:13:17.670 --> 00:13:19.200
inside a design tool?

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:21.330
And we found this is cool.

00:13:21.330 --> 00:13:24.750
Very quickly, I
can tell that wow,

00:13:24.750 --> 00:13:26.670
this is how big the
person is in the world.

00:13:26.670 --> 00:13:28.270
So we learned quite
a bit from that.

00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:30.560
It's fun to share with you.

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:33.766
Something else we found is that
standing and seated positions

00:13:33.766 --> 00:13:35.265
are pretty important
to think about.

00:13:35.265 --> 00:13:37.440
So if you stare at person,
it's like, we really

00:13:37.440 --> 00:13:38.450
have a person there.

00:13:38.450 --> 00:13:42.020
It's not just for cylinders.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:43.930
So people may be
sitting in their living

00:13:43.930 --> 00:13:47.850
room, unable to turn around,
so you place stuff around them.

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:49.820
Let's talk about
field of view now.

00:13:49.820 --> 00:13:53.160
So this prototype
shows two frustums.

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:54.910
Frustums are these
pyramid looking shapes.

00:13:54.910 --> 00:13:56.410
Sorry for the math
guys in the room.

00:13:56.410 --> 00:13:58.155
I've got to explain
it's like a pyramid.

00:13:58.155 --> 00:13:59.460
That's a frustum.

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:02.100
So the narrower one
that you see right now

00:14:02.100 --> 00:14:04.390
shows you what you can see
without turning your head.

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:05.720
So I think that in
there is pretty nice,

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:07.420
so you know when you
place an object there,

00:14:07.420 --> 00:14:09.586
as you move it into the
field of view of the person,

00:14:09.586 --> 00:14:11.980
is the person going to be
having to turn their head?

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:15.729
You build UI, you have that
distance in the green rings,

00:14:15.729 --> 00:14:17.770
and then you know if they
have to turn their head

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:21.210
to see anything or not.

00:14:21.210 --> 00:14:22.900
The wider one, the
black one there,

00:14:22.900 --> 00:14:25.880
shows you what you can see if
you turn your head slightly.

00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:27.020
It looks pretty wide.

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:29.450
Actually, it's just turning
your head comfortably.

00:14:29.450 --> 00:14:31.120
So it's nice to think
about when people

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:34.650
are unable to turn around as
you build your interfaces.

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:36.540
Just sharing with you
things we're trying.

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:39.360
Hope that's
interesting to look at.

