00:19:51.594 --> 00:19:53.510
So when you're designing
for VR, you're really

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:55.301
designing for the
capabilities of the human

00:19:55.301 --> 00:19:58.080
as much as you're designing for
the capabilities of the system,

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:00.371
so it's really important that
you understand your users

00:20:00.371 --> 00:20:02.200
and what they're capable of.

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:04.990
So first we'll start
out with a story.

00:20:04.990 --> 00:20:07.680
Imagine it's a beautiful morning
hundreds of thousands of years

00:20:07.680 --> 00:20:10.850
ago and you wake up and
you're feeling great.

00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:11.715
The sun is shining.

00:20:11.715 --> 00:20:14.550
You look outside your cave and
you don't see any predators.

00:20:14.550 --> 00:20:16.250
That's awesome.

00:20:16.250 --> 00:20:20.350
And you're starving so it's
time to start foraging for food.

00:20:20.350 --> 00:20:22.460
So you head out and
you find some berries,

00:20:22.460 --> 00:20:24.920
these red berries, and you've
never seen anything like this

00:20:24.920 --> 00:20:25.420
before.

00:20:25.420 --> 00:20:26.684
These look delicious.

00:20:26.684 --> 00:20:29.350
So you start eating them and you
realize immediately that things

00:20:29.350 --> 00:20:30.560
have gone horribly wrong.

00:20:30.560 --> 00:20:33.140
You've got this
ringing in your ears,

00:20:33.140 --> 00:20:34.720
your vision's a
little bit blurry,

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:37.180
and the worst part is
everything is kind of wooshy,

00:20:37.180 --> 00:20:39.020
like you move and the
world doesn't totally

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:40.320
track correctly.

00:20:40.320 --> 00:20:42.310
And this is a really
critical moment for you

00:20:42.310 --> 00:20:44.430
because you basically
have two options.

00:20:44.430 --> 00:20:47.730
You can eject the berries,
or if you don't, it's

00:20:47.730 --> 00:20:49.790
unfortunately game over.

00:20:49.790 --> 00:20:54.400
And we've evolved to be
very sensitive to vestibular

00:20:54.400 --> 00:20:55.940
ocular disparities.

00:20:55.940 --> 00:20:59.280
Motion sickness is actually
a defensive mechanism

00:20:59.280 --> 00:21:00.790
that comes through evolution.

00:21:00.790 --> 00:21:02.680
And the person that
ejected the berries,

00:21:02.680 --> 00:21:05.520
they're our ancestor
because they survived.

00:21:05.520 --> 00:21:09.335
So bad input can really cause
a bad physiological response

00:21:09.335 --> 00:21:10.960
for users, and this
is something that's

00:21:10.960 --> 00:21:13.277
really important with VR design.

00:21:13.277 --> 00:21:15.110
Of course, we're familiar
with phones having

00:21:15.110 --> 00:21:16.620
an inertial measurement unit.

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:18.720
We have one as well
called our cochlea.

00:21:18.720 --> 00:21:21.150
It's sort of a series
of tubes in our ear

00:21:21.150 --> 00:21:23.310
and in our vestibular system.

00:21:23.310 --> 00:21:25.844
And as we're thinking about
the system as a whole,

00:21:25.844 --> 00:21:27.760
we have the phone's
inertial measurement unit.

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:29.600
We also have our own.

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:32.230
We have the screen and
our eyes, and all of this

00:21:32.230 --> 00:21:35.331
has to work in tangent, in
unison as part of the system.

00:21:35.331 --> 00:21:36.830
So it's really
important that you're

00:21:36.830 --> 00:21:39.288
getting good input to the user
based off of their movements

00:21:39.288 --> 00:21:41.680
and what they're seeing
because if it doesn't, then

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:44.980
that's going to create bad
physiological responses.

00:21:44.980 --> 00:21:47.910
So this is a complex
way of saying always

00:21:47.910 --> 00:21:49.570
maintain head tracking.

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:51.020
Never drop frames.

00:21:51.020 --> 00:21:55.950
If you're starting to load a
new scene in your application,

00:21:55.950 --> 00:22:00.679
it's not OK to freeze all of
a sudden and let that come in.

00:22:00.679 --> 00:22:02.470
Be sure that you're
monitoring performance,

00:22:02.470 --> 00:22:04.522
that you're always
maintaining head tracking.

00:22:04.522 --> 00:22:05.730
It's really, really critical.

00:22:05.730 --> 00:22:08.050
If for any reason you
can't, just fade to black

00:22:08.050 --> 00:22:10.550
and keep using audio
in your application

00:22:10.550 --> 00:22:14.572
because people are very
sensitive to these things.

00:22:14.572 --> 00:22:16.780
Another thing to talk about
is motion and the concept

00:22:16.780 --> 00:22:18.270
of constant velocity.

00:22:18.270 --> 00:22:19.480
So it's kind of strange.

00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:20.850
We actually don't feel velocity.

00:22:20.850 --> 00:22:23.000
We feel acceleration
and deceleration.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.670
So an example of this is
when you're in an airplane,

00:22:25.670 --> 00:22:28.690
you definitely feel the take
off and you feel the landing,

00:22:28.690 --> 00:22:30.580
but when you're actually
just flying around,

00:22:30.580 --> 00:22:32.907
it doesn't feel like you're
going 500 miles per hour.

00:22:32.907 --> 00:22:34.740
You might feel some
turbulence or something,

00:22:34.740 --> 00:22:36.281
but the actual
velocity of the plane,

00:22:36.281 --> 00:22:38.594
you're not noticing that.

00:22:38.594 --> 00:22:39.260
Another example.

00:22:39.260 --> 00:22:41.070
We're all, of course,
on the planet Earth.

00:22:41.070 --> 00:22:42.576
It's traveling very fast.

00:22:42.576 --> 00:22:43.950
If the planet were
to decelerate,

00:22:43.950 --> 00:22:46.320
we would definitely feel
that, but while it's

00:22:46.320 --> 00:22:48.810
traveling at high velocity,
we're not feeling that at all.

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:50.880
So this fact that we
don't feel velocity

00:22:50.880 --> 00:22:53.000
is actually really
important for VR design

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.570
as well because if you
have someone traveling

00:22:55.570 --> 00:22:57.440
at a constant velocity,
it's not going

00:22:57.440 --> 00:22:59.220
to be as disconcerting
as if you're

00:22:59.220 --> 00:23:01.220
having lots of acceleration
and deceleration

00:23:01.220 --> 00:23:03.470
because they're going to
notice that difference, when,

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:06.011
if in VR they're accelerating
or decelerating, then obviously

00:23:06.011 --> 00:23:08.160
in reality, they're
just standing there.

00:23:08.160 --> 00:23:11.839
So that can also create
potentially some discomfort.

00:23:11.839 --> 00:23:12.880
And everyone's different.

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:14.600
Everyone has different
tolerance levels

00:23:14.600 --> 00:23:16.760
for what they find
acceptable with motion,

00:23:16.760 --> 00:23:19.380
so it's really important to
try things out with users, even

00:23:19.380 --> 00:23:21.610
with constant velocity,
to see how they're feeling

00:23:21.610 --> 00:23:24.250
and if it's working.

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:26.580
Another aspect about
motion is definitely keep

00:23:26.580 --> 00:23:29.820
a stable horizon line
inside your application.

00:23:29.820 --> 00:23:32.505
I'm sorry.

00:23:32.505 --> 00:23:35.990
If you don't, it'll--
don't drop frames, either.

00:23:35.990 --> 00:23:39.510
So let's talk about vision.

00:23:39.510 --> 00:23:42.314
A really common question with
vision that a lot of people

00:23:42.314 --> 00:23:43.730
talk about is what
resolution does

00:23:43.730 --> 00:23:47.444
the screen need to be for
resolution not to matter?

00:23:47.444 --> 00:23:48.610
It's a really good question.

00:23:48.610 --> 00:23:49.610
There's two parts of it.

00:23:49.610 --> 00:23:50.970
One is field of view.

00:23:50.970 --> 00:23:53.930
So again, everyone's different,
but for a lot of people,

00:23:53.930 --> 00:23:57.420
field of view of 210 degrees
horizontally by 100 degrees

00:23:57.420 --> 00:24:00.800
vertically will
cover everything.

00:24:00.800 --> 00:24:06.320
And then in terms of pixel
density, if for every degree,

00:24:06.320 --> 00:24:09.070
we had 60 by 60 pixels,
that would be pushing

00:24:09.070 --> 00:24:10.750
the limits of our vision.

00:24:10.750 --> 00:24:11.660
That would be 20/20.

00:24:11.660 --> 00:24:13.409
Some people have better
than 20/20 vision,

00:24:13.409 --> 00:24:18.030
so it's in that range of getting
up to 60 pixels per degree.

00:24:18.030 --> 00:24:20.740
So something like
a 12,600 screen

00:24:20.740 --> 00:24:23.994
by 6,000 with a 210 by 100
field of view would be great.

00:24:23.994 --> 00:24:25.660
That's probably
actually overshooting it

00:24:25.660 --> 00:24:27.534
because we actually only
have high resolution

00:24:27.534 --> 00:24:29.880
vision in our central
vision with our fovea.

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:31.890
Our peripheral vision
is very blurry.

00:24:31.890 --> 00:24:34.192
This is assuming that you
had the same size pixels

00:24:34.192 --> 00:24:35.400
throughout the entire screen.

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:37.200
You can build a
screen with pixels

00:24:37.200 --> 00:24:39.270
that were different sizes.

00:24:39.270 --> 00:24:43.090
So that's pretty high,
and we're not there yet.

00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:45.630
And as we are on this
progression of increasing

00:24:45.630 --> 00:24:47.906
screen technology
with phones, it

00:24:47.906 --> 00:24:49.655
seems like it's becoming
harder and harder

00:24:49.655 --> 00:24:50.682
to talk about screens.

00:24:50.682 --> 00:24:52.640
We, of course, have our
old favorites like VGA,

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:54.700
but the recent acronyms
are getting increasingly

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:58.800
ridiculous, plus we have all the
complexity of optics with VR.

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:00.869
So I'd like to talk
about something

00:25:00.869 --> 00:25:02.660
we've been talking
about on the team, which

00:25:02.660 --> 00:25:05.550
is a really clear way to talk
about this is just pixels

00:25:05.550 --> 00:25:08.210
per degree and the number
of degrees of field of view,

00:25:08.210 --> 00:25:10.260
and just focus on
those two things.

00:25:10.260 --> 00:25:14.320
So again, if we can get
into 60 pixels per degree,

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:17.130
now we're at an eye
limiting system.

00:25:17.130 --> 00:25:18.620
So reality, 60
pixels per degree,

00:25:18.620 --> 00:25:20.300
210 degrees field of view.

00:25:20.300 --> 00:25:22.700
Let's talk about
some of our devices.

00:25:22.700 --> 00:25:25.370
Nexus 5 on Cardboard,
not quite reality

00:25:25.370 --> 00:25:29.224
yet, 12 pixels per degree
and 85 degrees field of view.

00:25:29.224 --> 00:25:31.140
Nexus 6 on Cardboard
does a little bit better,

00:25:31.140 --> 00:25:33.500
increases up to 13,
but more notably

00:25:33.500 --> 00:25:38.240
increases the field of
view with the new Cardboard

00:25:38.240 --> 00:25:40.386
up to 100 degrees.

00:25:40.386 --> 00:25:42.010
Let's talk about
hearing now that we've

00:25:42.010 --> 00:25:43.800
talked about vision a bit.

00:25:43.800 --> 00:25:46.000
In a way, hearing is
kind of a type of vision.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:47.930
So the interesting
thing about hearing

00:25:47.930 --> 00:25:51.040
is it lets you see the
entire scene around you

00:25:51.040 --> 00:25:53.000
all at the same
time, and this can

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.350
help you build up a mental
model of what's there

00:25:55.350 --> 00:25:56.730
before you've even seen it.

00:25:56.730 --> 00:25:58.250
So let's try out an example.

00:25:58.250 --> 00:26:00.407
[BELL RINGING]

00:26:00.407 --> 00:26:02.990
So you guys all knew that there
was a bell there before I even

00:26:02.990 --> 00:26:03.880
turned to look at it.

00:26:03.880 --> 00:26:05.966
Let's try it again.

00:26:05.966 --> 00:26:07.466
There's supposed
to be another bell.

00:26:07.466 --> 00:26:09.170
[BELL RINGING]

00:26:09.170 --> 00:26:10.210
Sort of over there.

00:26:10.210 --> 00:26:14.280
So we're really good at
positioning audio spatially.

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:16.760
And what's important for
this in terms of design

00:26:16.760 --> 00:26:20.620
is if you have something
creating audio in a scene,

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:23.490
you can immediately cue
users in to it being there.

00:26:23.490 --> 00:26:28.267
So attaching a bell to your
interface is a bit much.

00:26:28.267 --> 00:26:29.850
You could just have
your interface hum

00:26:29.850 --> 00:26:31.939
or buzz or something
a little bit,

00:26:31.939 --> 00:26:34.480
but you can definitely direct
the user's attention with audio

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:36.646
and you can fill them in
as to the world around them

00:26:36.646 --> 00:26:38.557
by using spatial audio.

00:26:38.557 --> 00:26:40.890
Let's talk a little bit about
designing the environment.

00:26:40.890 --> 00:26:43.800
So one of the first
mistakes we've made

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:46.250
and most people
designing VR make

00:26:46.250 --> 00:26:48.480
is you drop user
into the environment

00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:49.610
and you're not really
thinking about where you're

00:26:49.610 --> 00:26:51.370
going to drop them in
so they immediately

00:26:51.370 --> 00:26:54.010
start colliding with an object.

00:26:54.010 --> 00:26:57.670
This is very disconcerting
and sort of uncomfortable.

00:26:57.670 --> 00:27:00.100
It's not literally uncomfortable
because it's virtual,

00:27:00.100 --> 00:27:03.430
but you look down and you see
something coming through you

00:27:03.430 --> 00:27:05.510
and it's not good.

00:27:05.510 --> 00:27:07.780
You feel uneasy about it.

00:27:07.780 --> 00:27:10.080
So we talked a lot about
physiological comfort.

00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:12.407
It's also important to talk
about environmental comfort

00:27:12.407 --> 00:27:14.740
and the types of things that
make people environmentally

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:15.750
uncomfortable.

00:27:15.750 --> 00:27:18.870
So obviously, heights
is a big one for people.

00:27:18.870 --> 00:27:20.760
People can be scared of heights.

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:24.194
Also small spaces,
claustrophobia.

00:27:24.194 --> 00:27:25.610
Then there's the
opposite of that.

00:27:25.610 --> 00:27:28.450
For me, actually, I'm
more with agoraphobia,

00:27:28.450 --> 00:27:31.180
large spaces, big, empty rooms.

00:27:31.180 --> 00:27:33.290
Imagine working at a desk
with a single spotlight

00:27:33.290 --> 00:27:34.280
down on your desk.

00:27:34.280 --> 00:27:37.547
That would be very unnerving.

00:27:37.547 --> 00:27:38.630
Scale is very interesting.

00:27:38.630 --> 00:27:40.130
So when you have
small objects, they

00:27:40.130 --> 00:27:41.810
have this sort of
toy-like quality.

00:27:41.810 --> 00:27:43.340
They're very fun.

00:27:43.340 --> 00:27:45.510
You feel very powerful.

00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:46.780
You're this giant.

00:27:46.780 --> 00:27:48.030
You have this tiny truck.

00:27:48.030 --> 00:27:51.560
But if you invert that,
now it's very different.

00:27:51.560 --> 00:27:54.430
You feel very weak and
small and very intimidated

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:55.400
by these big objects.

00:27:55.400 --> 00:27:57.300
It's not just
things like trucks.

00:27:57.300 --> 00:27:59.840
You could build a user
interface that was really big,

00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:02.530
and the user will feel small
and diminished in front of it,

00:28:02.530 --> 00:28:04.330
like the interface
itself will make user

00:28:04.330 --> 00:28:06.520
feel slightly uncomfortable.

00:28:06.520 --> 00:28:09.460
Other things about
environmental comfort.

00:28:09.460 --> 00:28:12.220
Obviously, people don't
like to be crushed.

00:28:12.220 --> 00:28:15.280
This is an extreme example,
but another example.

00:28:15.280 --> 00:28:17.780
I was in a VR simulation and
it was just planets rotating

00:28:17.780 --> 00:28:18.280
around.

00:28:18.280 --> 00:28:20.720
It was beautiful, but then
suddenly, one of the planets

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.120
was coming right out
me, and part of my brain

00:28:23.120 --> 00:28:26.380
was thinking, get out of
the way, get out of the way.

00:28:26.380 --> 00:28:27.764
You can't turn that off.

00:28:27.764 --> 00:28:29.680
And for that moment, it
was very uncomfortable

00:28:29.680 --> 00:28:31.497
as I had to remind
myself, no, it's fine.

00:28:31.497 --> 00:28:33.830
This planet is just going to
collide straight through me

00:28:33.830 --> 00:28:35.512
and everything's
going to be great.

00:28:35.512 --> 00:28:36.970
So people don't
like to be crushed.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:37.875
Also, sharp objects.

00:28:37.875 --> 00:28:40.680
People aren't super
fond of those.

00:28:40.680 --> 00:28:43.130
For sharp objects in
particular, people

00:28:43.130 --> 00:28:44.970
are very protective
of their eyes.

00:28:44.970 --> 00:28:47.160
So imagine you have a
meditation application that

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:50.370
has little hummingbirds in it,
and one of those hummingbirds

00:28:50.370 --> 00:28:52.190
floats up with its
little hummingbird beak

00:28:52.190 --> 00:28:53.620
right next to your eye.

00:28:53.620 --> 00:28:57.597
The user is going to recoil
away and defensively block,

00:28:57.597 --> 00:29:00.180
and that was not what you wanted
because this was a meditation

00:29:00.180 --> 00:29:00.680
application.

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:01.950
You're supposed to be relaxed.

00:29:01.950 --> 00:29:05.050
So the important thing
about environmental comfort

00:29:05.050 --> 00:29:07.570
is to be intentional,
to in testing,

00:29:07.570 --> 00:29:09.110
see the types of
things that people

00:29:09.110 --> 00:29:12.620
find unnerving for various
reasons, to think about it

00:29:12.620 --> 00:29:16.222
and then involve this as
part of your testing process.

00:29:16.222 --> 00:29:18.430
You're not just doing
physiological comfort, but also

00:29:18.430 --> 00:29:20.570
environmental comfort.

00:29:20.570 --> 00:29:22.580
So a quick note
about perspective.

00:29:22.580 --> 00:29:24.580
Almost all VR apps are
first person perspective,

00:29:24.580 --> 00:29:26.210
which makes a lot of sense.

00:29:26.210 --> 00:29:28.910
Third person perspective
is also really interesting.

00:29:28.910 --> 00:29:30.880
This is an app called
RoboBliteration.

00:29:30.880 --> 00:29:31.687
It's really fun.

00:29:31.687 --> 00:29:34.270
You have this little spaceship
that you control with your head

00:29:34.270 --> 00:29:36.281
and it moves on the
surface of an asteroid.

00:29:36.281 --> 00:29:38.280
So I think third person
perspective games for VR

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:40.470
are also super compelling
and we're probably

00:29:40.470 --> 00:29:42.990
going to see a lot more of them
be considered in the future

00:29:42.990 --> 00:29:45.050
as well.

00:29:45.050 --> 00:29:47.210
So moving on to
interaction design,

00:29:47.210 --> 00:29:50.060
for a system like Cardboard,
basically, all interaction

00:29:50.060 --> 00:29:51.850
is by moving your
head gaze at objects

00:29:51.850 --> 00:29:53.080
and then clicking on them.

00:29:53.080 --> 00:29:57.460
So you're casting this ray
out of your head to set focus.

00:29:57.460 --> 00:30:00.175
Something we've found is when
people first try Cardboard,

00:30:00.175 --> 00:30:01.550
they don't really
move their head

00:30:01.550 --> 00:30:03.799
very much because they haven't
really realized it yet.

00:30:03.799 --> 00:30:06.790
So they just hold Cardboard
up and they stand very still,

00:30:06.790 --> 00:30:09.430
and that can be a little
frustrating as a designer

00:30:09.430 --> 00:30:11.010
because you've
created all stuff.

00:30:11.010 --> 00:30:13.130
So something to do
with is you just

00:30:13.130 --> 00:30:15.239
have something interesting
offscreen just a little

00:30:15.239 --> 00:30:16.780
bit in their field
of view, something

00:30:16.780 --> 00:30:18.344
to course them to
took over at it,

00:30:18.344 --> 00:30:20.260
then they'll realize
that head tracking works.

00:30:20.260 --> 00:30:22.510
As soon as they've done even a
little bit of a head movement,

00:30:22.510 --> 00:30:24.020
they get it and
they start looking

00:30:24.020 --> 00:30:25.810
around all over the place.

00:30:25.810 --> 00:30:29.295
And then as you have users
starting to look around,

00:30:29.295 --> 00:30:30.670
think about designs
that actually

00:30:30.670 --> 00:30:32.050
leverage the whole canvas.

00:30:32.050 --> 00:30:34.210
We don't have to design
for these small, 2D devices

00:30:34.210 --> 00:30:36.467
anymore, so we can create
interfaces that actually

00:30:36.467 --> 00:30:38.050
surround and encompass
the user and do

00:30:38.050 --> 00:30:40.636
these really creative things
that haven't been possible

00:30:40.636 --> 00:30:42.340
in the past.

00:30:42.340 --> 00:30:44.450
There's tremendous
opportunity here.

00:30:44.450 --> 00:30:47.440
There's also some challenge
because the camera

00:30:47.440 --> 00:30:48.060
has free will.

00:30:48.060 --> 00:30:50.630
So from the perspective
of a director

00:30:50.630 --> 00:30:52.070
or a cinematographer
where they're

00:30:52.070 --> 00:30:53.590
very focused on
telling their story

00:30:53.590 --> 00:30:55.410
and controlling
everything, they're

00:30:55.410 --> 00:30:57.076
probably a little bit
scared of the fact

00:30:57.076 --> 00:30:58.630
that users can look anywhere.

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:01.090
How are we going
to deal with that?

00:31:01.090 --> 00:31:04.090
So there's a couple ways of
directing the user's attention.

00:31:04.090 --> 00:31:07.410
One of them is sort of
a brute force approach,

00:31:07.410 --> 00:31:09.020
just rotation on scene change.

00:31:09.020 --> 00:31:11.850
So say it's a spherical
video and the user's

00:31:11.850 --> 00:31:14.160
looking at a particular spot,
but the next spot that's

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:15.700
interesting is off to the side.

00:31:15.700 --> 00:31:17.950
As you're doing that scene
change and fading to black,

00:31:17.950 --> 00:31:19.730
you can actually just
rotate that sphere

00:31:19.730 --> 00:31:20.970
so that wherever
the user's looking,

00:31:20.970 --> 00:31:23.428
the next interesting thing is
going to be in front of them.

00:31:23.428 --> 00:31:26.092
Now, don't do the
rotation unless you're

00:31:26.092 --> 00:31:28.550
fading to black because that
could make the user very sick,

00:31:28.550 --> 00:31:30.640
having the world
spin all of a sudden,

00:31:30.640 --> 00:31:33.170
but that's one way of
directing the user's attention.

00:31:33.170 --> 00:31:37.460
Another way which is more subtle
is guiding the user with light.

00:31:37.460 --> 00:31:39.650
This is a really popular
one in video game design.

00:31:39.650 --> 00:31:42.480
So for people that are designing
levels for video games,

00:31:42.480 --> 00:31:45.790
you'll often notice that
you just know the right way

00:31:45.790 --> 00:31:46.940
to go through a level.

00:31:46.940 --> 00:31:50.400
You usually find the right
path and keep walking.

00:31:50.400 --> 00:31:53.630
If you're not paying
attention and you go back,

00:31:53.630 --> 00:31:56.290
you'll see that often, they're
really lighting your path very

00:31:56.290 --> 00:31:59.910
clearly, and that's how you just
intuitively know the right way

00:31:59.910 --> 00:32:03.040
to go, these very subtle
cues with the lighting.

00:32:03.040 --> 00:32:04.837
So we actually
have some examples

00:32:04.837 --> 00:32:06.420
about this in the
Cardboard Design Lab

00:32:06.420 --> 00:32:11.460
you can try out where people are
looking at the brightest parts.

00:32:11.460 --> 00:32:14.214
Another thing we've been
exploring is gaze cues.

00:32:14.214 --> 00:32:16.630
So this is where you're tracking
where the user's looking,

00:32:16.630 --> 00:32:18.132
this ray that
they're casting out,

00:32:18.132 --> 00:32:19.840
and then that's actually
having an impact

00:32:19.840 --> 00:32:21.030
on the world around them.

00:32:21.030 --> 00:32:23.580
So we have an example where
you look at constellations

00:32:23.580 --> 00:32:26.790
and they illuminate, which
is sort of an interesting way

00:32:26.790 --> 00:32:29.029
to make the world slightly
interactive with how

00:32:29.029 --> 00:32:30.820
the user is looking at
things and exploring

00:32:30.820 --> 00:32:32.880
more details of the world.

00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:37.420
You can also use gaze cues
as a very technical technique

00:32:37.420 --> 00:32:40.440
as you're staging things
out in your VR application.

00:32:40.440 --> 00:32:41.910
So in the lab
right before, we're

00:32:41.910 --> 00:32:45.050
actually teaching spatial
audio, the bell thing,

00:32:45.050 --> 00:32:46.720
although in this
case, it's not a bell.

00:32:46.720 --> 00:32:47.910
We have an owl.

00:32:47.910 --> 00:32:51.330
When you look at the fire,
that triggers the owl appearing

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:53.080
because at this point,
we know that you're

00:32:53.080 --> 00:32:54.590
looking at the fire.

00:32:54.590 --> 00:32:55.490
And we know you're going
to look at the fire

00:32:55.490 --> 00:32:57.090
because it's the
brightest thing.

00:32:57.090 --> 00:32:59.610
So we're actually staging
the owl coming out

00:32:59.610 --> 00:33:02.280
off of a gaze queue, and
then the owl shows up.

00:33:02.280 --> 00:33:03.835
It's sort of a jump scare owl.

00:33:03.835 --> 00:33:06.180
It's kind of fun.

00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:09.980
So the final thing about
interaction design.

00:33:09.980 --> 00:33:12.840
Let's talk about in
world user interfaces.

00:33:12.840 --> 00:33:15.824
So the important thing
to note with VR design

00:33:15.824 --> 00:33:17.240
is you can design
the whole world,

00:33:17.240 --> 00:33:19.619
so you don't have
to build interfaces

00:33:19.619 --> 00:33:22.160
in that world for the user to
use as much as you can actually

00:33:22.160 --> 00:33:25.270
embody those interfaces
in the world itself.

00:33:25.270 --> 00:33:27.890
So one developer in the
industry spoke about this

00:33:27.890 --> 00:33:30.480
as don't have a
little health bar--

00:33:30.480 --> 00:33:32.000
say you're flying a spaceship.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:33.890
Instead, look out and
actually see the damage

00:33:33.890 --> 00:33:35.140
on the wing of your spaceship.

00:33:35.140 --> 00:33:37.181
That's a much more
interesting and compelling way

00:33:37.181 --> 00:33:38.660
to convey that same information.

00:33:38.660 --> 00:33:40.860
Don't have all these
little meta indicators

00:33:40.860 --> 00:33:42.840
that are built in
because you can actually

00:33:42.840 --> 00:33:46.680
expose that interface
in the world design.

00:33:46.680 --> 00:33:49.180
And across the board, as we've
been doing all of this design

00:33:49.180 --> 00:33:53.170
work, something we found is that
VR is a really powerful medium.

00:33:53.170 --> 00:33:55.180
And there's three
things that happened

00:33:55.180 --> 00:33:59.370
to be recently that
convinced me of this,

00:33:59.370 --> 00:34:02.320
just fundamentally convinced
me VR is incredibly powerful.

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:04.110
The first one is
I actually forgot

00:34:04.110 --> 00:34:08.070
I was in VR, which is maybe
a little embarrassing.

00:34:08.070 --> 00:34:10.670
This was a couple weeks ago.

00:34:10.670 --> 00:34:13.780
So I was sitting in a
movie theater simulation.

00:34:13.780 --> 00:34:15.822
I was at work, and I
was watching trailers,

00:34:15.822 --> 00:34:17.280
and I hadn't seen
the trailers yet,

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:18.679
so they were kind
of interesting.

00:34:18.679 --> 00:34:20.970
And then I was really worried
because I haven't started

00:34:20.970 --> 00:34:23.409
preparing for my I/O talk yet.

00:34:23.409 --> 00:34:25.449
So I've got multiple
levels of distraction going

00:34:25.449 --> 00:34:28.500
on there with the trailers
and also the worrying,

00:34:28.500 --> 00:34:30.770
and then some people right
next to me started talking,

00:34:30.770 --> 00:34:33.389
and I turned, and
there was no one there.

00:34:33.389 --> 00:34:36.469
And I thought, that's weird.

00:34:36.469 --> 00:34:37.360
It's not right.

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:41.877
And then I realized, oh,
it's because I'm in VR.

00:34:41.877 --> 00:34:43.710
That was the first time
that happened to me.

00:34:43.710 --> 00:34:46.239
So I think with
enough distraction,

00:34:46.239 --> 00:34:48.219
our minds are set
up to start taking

00:34:48.219 --> 00:34:49.889
the input they're getting.

00:34:49.889 --> 00:34:51.962
So you can have
these moments where--

00:34:51.962 --> 00:34:54.170
I mean, we have this even
when you're reading a book,

00:34:54.170 --> 00:34:55.753
you get lost in the
story of the book,

00:34:55.753 --> 00:34:57.880
so it's very easy for people
to get lost in things.

00:34:57.880 --> 00:35:00.170
But getting lost in
VR is quite something.

00:35:02.680 --> 00:35:05.390
The second thing that we
found very interesting

00:35:05.390 --> 00:35:07.580
as a team is the
industry has talked a lot

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:09.740
about presence, this
notion of accepting

00:35:09.740 --> 00:35:13.250
the simulation as reality for
a moment and rolling with it.

00:35:13.250 --> 00:35:16.340
Even more interesting
is pairing presence

00:35:16.340 --> 00:35:19.350
with the psychological
concept of flow

00:35:19.350 --> 00:35:24.240
where your creativity is
just completely engaged.

00:35:24.240 --> 00:35:27.200
In this case, with the
application Tilt Brush,

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:28.970
you're just lost,
not just in VR,

00:35:28.970 --> 00:35:31.020
but you're also lost
in the creative task

00:35:31.020 --> 00:35:32.560
of sculpting and painting.

00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:34.518
And this can be a really
interesting experience

00:35:34.518 --> 00:35:39.020
when you just spend long periods
of time creating things in VR.

00:35:39.020 --> 00:35:41.580
And then the third thing
that's really struck me

00:35:41.580 --> 00:35:44.300
about VR interface
design is when

00:35:44.300 --> 00:35:46.080
you're thinking back
to VR experiences

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:47.480
you had a long time ago.

00:35:47.480 --> 00:35:50.040
So because you're engaging
so much of your mind,

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:52.370
like all of your spatial
memory, your sense of self

00:35:52.370 --> 00:35:55.229
is being engaged with VR,
you know it's not real

00:35:55.229 --> 00:35:57.770
and you can think back and you
know it wasn't real back then,

00:35:57.770 --> 00:35:59.860
but you're still storing
a lot of that experience

00:35:59.860 --> 00:36:02.420
as if it was a place
or as if it was a thing

00:36:02.420 --> 00:36:03.690
that you actually did.

00:36:03.690 --> 00:36:06.990
So thinking back to
VR, you're really

00:36:06.990 --> 00:36:09.530
for the first time
creating users' memories,

00:36:09.530 --> 00:36:11.440
and this is amazing
as a designer

00:36:11.440 --> 00:36:15.380
because now we can really
design rich experiences

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:17.995
that people think of as
places and as experiences

00:36:17.995 --> 00:36:19.670
that they've had.

00:36:19.670 --> 00:36:23.420
So this is something the team's
incredibly excited about.

00:36:23.420 --> 00:36:25.270
Current contributions
so far, of course,

00:36:25.270 --> 00:36:27.140
go get the Cardboard
Design Lab to try out

00:36:27.140 --> 00:36:28.480
a lot of the VR principles.

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:31.310
We also have a lot of
documentation online,

00:36:31.310 --> 00:36:33.036
and of course, the
SDK is available.

